# OS keychain / Credential Manager naming

- **Provider id** in config and CLI is **`os.secrets`** (`OsKeychainSecretProvider`); canonical ids live in `packages/runtime/src/secrets/provider-ids.ts`.
- **Service name** (keyring “service” / grouping for `findCredentials`): `ecp` — see `ECP_KEYRING_SERVICE` in `packages/runtime/src/secrets/constants.ts`.
- **Storage target** (per-secret): `ecp://<logical-key>` via `osKeychainCredentialTarget` / `secretRefIdFromLogicalKey`, created with `Entry.withTarget(target, ECP_KEYRING_SERVICE, username)` so Windows does not synthesize `username.service` targets like `ecp.KEY.ecp`. The provider id is **not** part of the URI (`os.secrets` stays on `SecretRef.provider` / binding `source`).
- **Username** field passed to the keyring is the canonical logical key (`canonicalSecretKeyForOsStorage`: trim, `\` → `/`).
- **`normalizeOsKeychainAccountKey`** remains for dotted `ecp.*` legacy helpers only; do not use it for `store` / `load` / `delete` on `OsKeychainSecretProvider`.
- **`list`** maps OS `account` strings to `SecretRef` (handles either logical usernames or full `ecp://…` targets).
